Apterous form (
Figs. 1–2
). General color dark brown. Rostrum, first antennomere, head, anterior lobe and posterior margin of pronotum, and femora of all legs pale brown to yellowish-brown; some specimens with abdominal tergites reddish-brown. Venter of body brown-yellow. Venter of head, mesosternum and metasternum dark brown. Dorsum covered by short, recumbent black setae. Venter covered by short, recumbent yellow setae. Legs hairy. Cephalic trichobothria quite long, the posterior pair inserted at the margin of the basal constriction of the head capsule, the two anterior pairs inserted close together at the level of the frons, near eyes.

Median length of abdominal tergites as follows: I: 0.24 , II–III: 0.52 , IV–VI and VIII: 0.60 , VII: 0.84 . Abdominal mediotergites I–III with wide and glabrous channels. Connexiva angled upward at 40 º, with margins of segments II–VI thickened. Connexival margins straight and evenly convergent posteriorly (
Fig. 2
). Apical margin of ventrite VI slightly concave centrally (
Fig. 9
). Ventrite VIII strongly depressed at the midline. Genital segments large and distinctly protruding from the end of the pregenital abdomen. Proctiger with two lateral, conspicuous and divergent prolongations in dorsal basal half (
Fig. 10
). Genital capsule as in
Fig. 11
; pygophore (
Fig. 12
); claspers symmetrical, relatively large, with oval tip ( Figs. 11 , 13 ).

Hind legs distinctly longer than others (
Fig. 2
). Male grasping comb extending for about three-fifths of fore tibia (
Fig. 14
). Middle and hind coxae slightly longer than fore coxae and inserted laterally to body center (
Fig. 8
). Femora slightly incrassate, lacking spines or spinose setae. Tibiae slender, straight, with grooming structures at apex (
Fig. 15
). Tarsi three-segmented; with first segments small, and subtriangular, and claws subterminal.

Apterous female (
Fig. 1
). Length 9.8 , maximum width 2.6 ; distinctly larger than male. Length of antennomeres I–IV: 1.30 , 1.20 , 0.88 , 0.70 . Abdomen with 8 mediotergites and 6 laterotergites (
Fig. 1
). Median length of abdominal tergites as follows: I: 0.24 , II: 0.64 , III: 0.60 , IV: 0.88 , V: 0.72 , VI: 0.76 , VII: 0.80 , VIII: 0.4 . Margins of connexival segments I–IV subparallel; margins of connexival segments V–VI caudally convergent; last laterotergite infolded and almost completely covering abdominal tergites VII and VIII (
Fig. 1
); connexiva ending in short spines (
Fig. 16
).

Comparative notes.
Paravelia daza
sp. n.
is a large ( 9.2–9.8 ), brown species. It may be recognized by the length of the head three times the length of an eye (
Fig. 3
); the male connexiva angled upward at 40 º, with parallel margins (
Fig. 2
); and the oval flat side of the apex of the paramere (
Fig. 12
). The female connexiva are infolded, covering abdominal tergites VI–VIII (
Fig. 1
), and the female genital structures are as described in
Figs. 16–20
. Males and the females bear a grasping comb on fore tibia (
Fig. 14
), and all tibiae have grooming structures (
Fig. 15
).
